**User Login Function in PHP**
=====================================

Below is an example of a simple user login function written in PHP. This code will check the username and password provided by the user against a predefined array of usernames and passwords.

### `login.php`

```php
<?php
// Define a function to handle user login
function login_user($username, $password) {
    // Predefined array of usernames and passwords for demonstration purposes only!
    $users = [
        "admin" => "secret",
        "user1" => "password123"
    ];

    // Check if the username exists in the users array
    if (array_key_exists($username, $users)) {
        // Check if the provided password matches the stored password
        if ($password === $users[$username]) {
            return true; // Login successful!
        } else {
            echo "Invalid password for user '$username'.";
            return false;
        }
    } else {
        echo "User '$username' not found.";
        return false;
    }
}

// Example usage:
if (isset($_POST['login'])) {
    $username = $_POST['username'];
    $password = $_POST['password'];

    // Call the login_user function
    if (login_user($username, $password)) {
        echo "Login successful!";
    } else {
        echo "Login failed.";
    }
}
?>
```

### `index.php` (Example HTML form)

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Login Form</title>
</head>
<body>

<form action="" method="post">
    <label for="username">Username:</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="username" name="username"><br>
    <label for="password">Password:</label><br>
    <input type="password" id="password" name="password"><br>
    <button type="submit" name="login">Login</button>
</form>

<?php require_once 'login.php'; ?>

</body>
</html>
```

**Note:** This example uses a simple array to store usernames and passwords, which is not secure for actual use. In a production environment, consider using a robust password hashing library (e.g., `password_hash()`) and storing the hashed passwords in a database.

### Security Considerations

*   **Use prepared statements or parameterized queries** to prevent SQL injection.
*   **Hash and store passwords securely**, using libraries like `password_hash()` and `password_verify()`.
*   **Use HTTPS (TLS)** to encrypt data transmitted between client and server.

